******
[3] Japan: insufficient vaccine stock
Date: 21 Sep 2016
Source: The Asahi Shimbun [edited]
http://www.asahi.com/ajw/articles/AJ201609210056.html


Measles is rapidly spreading in Japan, with 115 confirmed cases this year [2016] so far, but the nation appears to hold insufficient stocks of an immunization vaccine for everyone who needs it.

"Some experts and medical organizations are complaining that there is not enough vaccine," said members of an expert panel at the health ministry. The nation's measles vaccination program should be given top priority, the panel members added.

Of the 115 cases confirmed this year by 11 Sep [2016], 96 of those occurred within the last 4 weeks, according to preliminary figures released on 20 Sep 2016 by the Tokyo-based National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID). That compares to just 35 cases of measles recorded in Japan in 2015.

The current outbreak of the infection gathered pace at Kansai International Airport, Osaka Prefecture, where it spread among workers from mid-August [2016]. Many of those infected work at counters for international flights.

According to the NIID, Osaka Prefecture currently has the highest number of cases at 43, followed by Hyogo and Chiba prefectures with 21 each and Tokyo with 11. The confirmed cases are mainly among babies, toddlers and children. 90 percent of those infected are under 40 years old.

Measles is a highly contagious disease caused by an airborne virus. The vaccination shot is effective in preventing its spread.

[Byline: Yusuke Ogawa]

